    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Cookie the Monkey: Home Is Where the Heart Is</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Fred Baumgarten letter asks how removing money named Cookie from Brooklyn family would benefit anyone, least of all Cookie or her wild relatives (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Family's Monkey Is Rare, and So Is Its Legal Battle'' (front page, July 19):</p>
        <p>While I agree that possessing an endangered species is wrong, I fail to see how removing one monkey from a family and moving her to a zoo is going to benefit anyone, least of all the monkey, Cookie, or her wild relatives.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Family's Monkey Is Rare, and So Is Its Legal Battle'' (front page, July 19):</p>
        <p>While I agree that possessing an endangered species is wrong, I fail to see how removing one monkey from a family and moving her to a zoo is going to benefit anyone, least of all the monkey, Cookie, or her wild relatives.</p>
        <p>The New York State Department of Environmental Conservation ought to be concentrating on solving the root problem: preventing the illicit import and sale of endangered species.</p>
        <p>FRED BAUMGARTEN  Sharon, Conn., July 19, 2000</p>
      </block>
